Male terminalia
(
Figs. 9–11
): Epandrium (
Figs. 9, 10
) as for genus. Phallus (
Fig. 11
) as for genus, bubble-like structure large, about 1.5 times as long as part of sclerotization distal to bubble.

Female terminalia
(
Figs. 13, 15
): Oviscape slightly longer than tergite 6, yellowish, with black apex. Aculeus (
Fig. 13
a): aculeus-width-ratio averages 2.14 (range: 1.91–2.37); aculeus-shoulders-ratio averages 2.02 (range: 1.84–2.21); serration of arrow-head apex averaging 13.3 teeth (range: 11–15; 
Fig.13
b). Spermathecae (
Fig. 15
) mostly spherical or ovoid (up to about 1.5 times as wide as long; 
Fig. 15
a), sometimes elongate (up to about twice as long as wide; 
Fig. 15
b).

Fruits collected on Mt. Hermon (see Material Examined) in summer 2004 contained larvae that pupated during the next few months. Adults from the same lot of pupae emerged in the next spring (2005), but also in the spring of 2008, demostrating that adult flies can emerge up to at least four years after pupation. This is a phenological phenomenon that, although possibly more common than expected, has seldom been reported in the literature (
Bateman, 1972
).
